    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the confusion earlier; I will stick strictly to the technical debugging steps for your automotive ECU project. Since you are working with a Real-Time Operating System (RTOS), the tools you need depend heavily on whether your heap is managed by the RTOS kernel itself or by a custom allocator.\n\nIf your RTOS has built-in memory management (like FreeRTOS), you should utilize the built-in heap statistics provided by the kernel. In FreeRTOS, for example, you can enable the `configUSE_MALLOC_FAILED_HOOK` and `configUSE_MALLOC_FAILED_HOOK` to track allocation failures, but more importantly, you can use the `xPortGetFreeHeapSize()` function to monitor available heap space in real-time. You can hook into the `vPortMalloc` function to log every allocation and deallocation event, which will help you identify if specific objects are being allocated but never freed.\n\nIf you are using a custom heap allocator or a third-party library like Mbed OS's heap, you should instrument the `new` and `delete` operators or the underlying `malloc`/`free` calls. A common technique is to wrap these functions with a logging layer that records the allocation size, the thread ID, and the timestamp",
